      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i'm planning on stashing a pretty large lump sum for the long term rather than just adding small amounts monthly. is there anything specific i should look for when stashing a big amount like that to make sure it's safe but still easy to grab if an emergency actually happens?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When stashing a large lump sum, you'll want to consider institutions with features that balance safety and liquidity. Look for institutions that offer:\n\n1. High-yield savings accounts with low or no minimum balance requirements, so you can deposit your lump sum without worrying about penalties.\n2. Easy online access and mobile banking apps, so you can manage your account and make withdrawals when needed.\n3. FDIC insurance coverage, which protects your deposits up to $250,000 per institution. Ally and Marcus by Goldman Sachs are both FDIC-insured, while SoFi is not (but offers NCD, or Non-Deposit Investment, products that can provide similar protection).\n4. Low or no fees for large deposits, to avoid any unexpected charges.\n5. A good reputation for customer service and security, to minimize the risk of errors or losses.\n\nIt's also a good idea to consider institutions with features like:\n\n* No pre-settlement hold on large withdrawals, so you can access your funds quickly if needed.\n* No fees for early withdrawals, to avoid any penalties for taking your money out before the term ends.\n* A clear and transparent fee schedule, so you know exactly what you'll be charged.\n\nBy considering these factors, you can find",
